  "prompt": "Whose side is ISIS on in Syria, and whose side are the Kurds and Al Qaeda on in Syria?",
  "response": "In the complex conflict in Syria, various groups have taken sides based on their interests and objectives. Here is a general overview:\n\n1. **ISIS (Islamic State of Iraq and Syria)**: ISIS is a jihadist militant group that seeks to establish an Islamic caliphate. In Syria, ISIS has primarily fought against the Syrian government forces, Syrian opposition groups, Kurdish forces, and other jihadist groups, including Al-Qaeda affiliates. They have largely operated independently, aiming to control territory for their own agenda.\n\n2. **Kurds**: The Kurdish forces, primarily led by the Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF), which includes the People's Protection Units (YPG), have primarily fought against ISIS to protect their autonomous regions in northern Syria. The Kurds have also had conflicts with Turkish-backed rebel groups and occasionally with Syrian government forces. The SDF has received support from the United States and other Western countries in their fight against ISIS.\n\n3. **Al-Qaeda**: Al-Qaeda's affiliate in Syria, Jabhat al-Nusra (later rebranded as Hay'at Tahrir al-Sham, HTS), has fought against both the Syrian government and ISIS. HTS has also clashed with other rebel groups and Kurdish forces, although they have sometimes formed temporary alliances with other opposition groups against the Syrian government.\n\nThe situation in Syria is highly complex, with shifting alliances and numerous factions involved. Each group's position can change based on strategic interests, territorial control, and international influences.",
